section.para:
A Document is created from a piece of text and starts with no layers:
Document document = Document.of("Rockwell International Corp. said it signed an agreement.");
The original text is always available and is never rewritten to a derived form:
CharSequence text = document.text();

			A document exposes the layers it holds, the annotations on any one layer, and a method
			that returns a new document with an added layer.
			List<Annotation<String>> tokens = List.of(
    new Annotation<>(new Span(0, 8), "Rockwell"));

Document tokenized = document.with(Layers.TOKENS, tokens);

Set<LayerKey<?>> present = tokenized.layers();       // contains Layers.TOKENS
List<Annotation<String>> readBack = tokenized.get(Layers.TOKENS);
			The original document is unchanged by with: it still has no
			token layer, while tokenized carries it. A document holds at most one layer
			per key, so with rejects an attempt to add a layer the document already has;
			an annotator produces a layer once. Reading a layer that is not present returns an empty
			list rather than null.

			A DocumentAnnotator reads the layers it needs from a document and returns a
			document with the layer it produces added. The interface is small:
			public interface DocumentAnnotator {

  Document annotate(Document document);

  default Set<LayerKey<?>> requires() {
    return Set.of();
  }

  Set<LayerKey<?>> provides();
}
			The requires and provides sets declare the annotator's
			place in a pipeline: what layers must already be present for it to run, and what layers
			it adds. An annotator that needs nothing keeps the default empty requires.

			Once the document is analyzed, its layers are read back with the same keys the
			annotators used to write them:
			List<Annotation<String>> tokens = document.get(Layers.TOKENS);
List<Annotation<String>> tags = document.get(Layers.POS_TAGS);

for (int i = 0; i < tokens.size(); i++) {
  Span span = tokens.get(i).span();
  System.out.println(tokens.get(i).value() + "/" + tags.get(i).value()
      + " at [" + span.getStart() + ".." + span.getEnd() + "]");
}

			An application adds its own analysis by implementing DocumentAnnotator. The
			annotator below reads the token layer and produces a layer of acronyms, tokens of two or
			more characters that are written entirely in uppercase letters. It declares its own key,
			requires TOKENS, and provides the new layer.
			public class AcronymAnnotator implements DocumentAnnotator {

  public static final LayerKey<String> ACRONYMS =
      LayerKey.of("acronyms", String.class);

  @Override
  public Set<LayerKey<?>> requires() {
    return Set.of(Layers.TOKENS);
  }

  @Override
  public Set<LayerKey<?>> provides() {
    return Set.of(ACRONYMS);
  }

  @Override
  public Document annotate(Document document) {
    List<Annotation<String>> acronyms = new ArrayList<>();
    for (Annotation<String> token : document.get(Layers.TOKENS)) {
      if (isAcronym(token.value())) {
        acronyms.add(new Annotation<>(token.span(), token.value()));
      }
    }
    return document.with(ACRONYMS, acronyms);
  }

  private static boolean isAcronym(String form) {
    if (form.length() < 2) {
      return false;
    }
    for (int i = 0; i < form.length(); i++) {
      if (!Character.isUpperCase(form.charAt(i))) {
        return false;
      }
    }
    return true;
  }
}
			Reusing the token span for each acronym keeps the new layer anchored to the same
			original-text offsets as the tokens it was derived from. The annotator drops into a
			pipeline like any other, and because it declares that it requires TOKENS,
			the builder guarantees a tokenizer runs before it.
